<southBL Sync="TRUE">53.963794</southBL></GeoBndBox></geoEle></dataExt><idPurp>Special Protection Areas (SPAs) are designated under The Conservation (Natural Habitats, etc.) Regulations (Northern Ireland) 1995 (as amended). Post transition the UK is still required to identify internationally important areas for breeding, over-wintering, and migrating birds and designate them as Special Protection Areas (SPAs).</idPurp><idAbs>&lt;DIV STYLE="text-align:Left;"&gt;&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;P STYLE="text-align:Justify;"&gt;&lt;SPAN&gt;Special Protection Areas (SPAs) are designated under the Conservation (Natural Habitats, etc.) Regulations (Northern Ireland) 1995 (as amended). These regulations implemented the Habitats Directive and will continue to apply after 1 January 2021. Some operability changes have been made through the Conservation (Natural Habitats, etc.) (Amendment) (Northern Ireland) (EU Exit) Regulations 2019. &lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P STYLE="text-align:Justify;"&gt;&lt;SPAN&gt;SPAs contribute to a UK national site network on land and at sea, including both the inshore and offshore marine areas. They are classified for rare and vulnerable birds (as listed on Annex I of the Birds Directive(79/409/EEC as amended), and for regularly occurring migratory species. The European Commission's website hosts a full copy of the EC Directive on the conservation of wild birds (79/409/EEC), within which all the Articles and Annexes (including amendments) are given, along with useful interpretation information.&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;SPAN /&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;</idAbs><idCredit>Organisation Name: Northern Ireland Environment Agency
